To align a row of divs to the right using Flexbox, you can use the `justify-content` property and set it to `flex-end`. Here's an example:

HTML:
```html
<div class="container">
  <div class="child">Child 1</div>
  <div class="child">Child 2</div>
  <div class="child">Child 3</div>
</div>
```
CSS:
```css
.container {
  display: flex;
  justify-content: flex-end;
}

.child {
  background-color: #f0f0f0;
  padding: 10px;
  margin-right: 10px;
}
```
In this example, the `.container` div is set to `display: flex`, which enables Flexbox layout. The `justify-content` property is then set to `flex-end`, which aligns the child elements (`.child`) to the right.

The result is:

Child 3
Child 2
Child 1

Note that you can also use other values for `justify-content`, such as `flex-start` (default), `center`, or `space-between`, depending on your desired alignment.
